// Completeness + the editor's hide layer. The compiler records a type for EVERY binding (the node->type
// map is complete); the editor then HIDES the redundant definition-forms by default via its small
// exception list — func/proc/sys/policy/enum/arche — and shows the rest; --full opts out. The split is
// SYNTACTIC: an enum decl's type is the `type` meta, identical to an alias's, yet enum HIDES (its RHS is
// `enum{…}`, a form) while an alias shows. A static ARRAY always carries a written type so its inlay is
// suppressed regardless; its fact lives in the map but isn't observable here.
// Default view — value/inferred bindings show (top-level value-const + static scalar, and locals):
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 20 8 1 1 type i32"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 21 8 1 1 type i32"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 28 6 1 1 type i32"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 30 6 1 1 type Color"
// exactly four by default — enum, the func/proc forms, and the two annotated bindings are all hidden:
// RUN: test $(%build/arche-analyzer --dump %s 2>/dev/null | grep -cF " type ") -eq 4
// --full opts out: enum (the `type` meta) and the func/proc forms then render too:
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump --full %s | grep -qxF "SYN 22 8 1 1 type type"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump --full %s | grep -qxF "SYN 24 6 1 1 type func(i32, i32) -> i32"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump --full %s | grep -qxF "SYN 27 7 1 1 type proc()()"
// RUN: test $(%build/arche-analyzer --dump --full %s 2>/dev/null | grep -cF " type ") -eq 7
#import { fmt }
total :: 100;
count := 0;
Color :: enum { Red, Green, Blue }
typed_g: int = 7;
add :: func(a: int, b: int) -> int {
  return a + b;
}
main :: proc() {
  x := 5;
  y: int = 9;
  c := Color.Red;
  fmt.printf("%d %d %d %d %d\n", total, count, add(x, y), typed_g, c);
}